This mention of “Jim Crow” was not something I had come across in the notable works I had read on Northern racial prejudice during my early explorations.
Figurines, touted as the “complete, original Jim Crow,” showed up on tables at annual spring fairs in Massachusetts.
Boston merchants carried music boxes that played “Jim Crow, Zip Coon and other tunes.” A tour of England widened his reputation.
The conductor laid down the usual ultimatum: the Jim Crow car or ejection.
The railroads, saved from state interference, took Adams’s hint: By the end of 1843, the Jim Crow cars were gone from the state’s railways.